---
import Base from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
import {
  BRAND_NAME,
  SITE_URL,
  PARENT_ORG_URL,
  GITHUB_REPO_URL,
} from "@/lib/config";
import { breadcrumbListSchema } from "@/lib/schema";
import {
  PENALTY_CODE_ORDER,
  PENALTY_META,
  MAX_TOTAL_PENALTY,
} from "@/lib/penalties";

const canonical = `${SITE_URL}/methodology`;
const jsonLd = breadcrumbListSchema([
  { name: "Home", url: SITE_URL },
  { name: "Methodology", url: canonical },
]);
---

<Base
  title={`Methodology | ${BRAND_NAME}`}
  description="How HumanizerBench tests AI humanizers: sample selection, scoring formula, versioning, full reproducibility."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage={`${SITE_URL}/og/methodology.png`}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>
  <article
    class="max-w-3xl mx-auto py-16 px-6 text-[var(--color-text-primary)] [&_h1]:text-4xl [&_h1]:font-semibold [&_h1]:tracking-tight [&_h1]:mb-8 [&_h2]:text-2xl [&_h2]:font-semibold [&_h2]:tracking-tight [&_h2]:mt-12 [&_h2]:mb-4 [&_h3]:text-lg [&_h3]:font-semibold [&_h3]:tracking-tight [&_h3]:mt-8 [&_h3]:mb-2 [&_p]:mt-4 [&_p]:leading-relaxed [&_p]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_ul]:mt-4 [&_ul]:space-y-2 [&_ul]:pl-6 [&_ul]:list-disc [&_ul]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_ol]:mt-4 [&_ol]:space-y-2 [&_ol]:pl-6 [&_ol]:list-decimal [&_ol]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_a]:text-[var(--color-accent)] [&_a:hover]:underline [&_code]:font-mono [&_code]:text-[0.9em] [&_code]:px-1 [&_code]:py-0.5 [&_code]:rounded [&_code]:bg-[var(--color-surface)] [&_code]:border [&_code]:border-[var(--color-border)] [&_strong]:font-semibold [&_strong]:text-[var(--color-text-primary)] [&_table]:mt-4 [&_table]:w-full [&_table]:text-sm [&_th]:text-left [&_th]:font-semibold [&_th]:px-3 [&_th]:py-2 [&_th]:border-b [&_th]:border-[var(--color-border)] [&_td]:px-3 [&_td]:py-2 [&_td]:border-b [&_td]:border-[var(--color-border)] [&_td]:text-[var(--color-text-secondary)] [&_td]:align-top"
  >
    <h1>Methodology</h1>

    <div
      class="rounded-lg border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-5 text-sm leading-relaxed text-[var(--color-text-secondary)]"
    >
      HumanizerBench is operated by WriteHuman (<a href={PARENT_ORG_URL}
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
        target="_blank">writehuman.ai</a
      >). We disclose this openly. The benchmark is fully reproducible: every
      input, every humanized output, every detector verdict, and the scoring
      algorithm itself are published per cycle in our
      <a href={GITHUB_REPO_URL} rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank"
        >public repository</a
      >. <strong class="text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"
        >Read our <a href="/fairness">fairness policy</a> or <a href="/why"
          >why we built this</a
        >.</strong
      >
    </div>

    <h2>Sample selection</h2>
    <p>
      Each cycle tests humanizers against samples spanning eight writing
      categories:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>academic_essay</code>: argumentative essays, lit-review intros</li>
      <li><code>application_essay</code>: personal statements, cover letters</li>
      <li><code>blog_post</code>: listicles, how-to guides</li>
      <li><code>marketing_copy</code>: product descriptions, landing pages</li>
      <li><code>business_email</code>: internal team announcements</li>
      <li><code>discussion_board</code>: discussion-board responses</li>
      <li><code>technical_doc</code>: API documentation</li>
      <li><code>news_article</code>: news article writing</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The full template set, with target word counts and the placeholder tokens
      each contains, is published per cycle as <code
        >data/cycles/&lt;cycle&gt;/templates.json</code
      >. Source-LLM outputs (the texts each humanizer is asked to rewrite) are
      published as <code>samples.json</code>. Per-cycle sample counts are
      recorded in <code>cycle.json</code> and on <code>leaderboard.json</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each template contains <code>[BRACKETED]</code> placeholder tokens
      (<code>[TOPIC]</code>, <code>[ROLE]</code>, <code>[FIELD]</code>, etc.).
      At cycle creation we fill every token from a curated value bank using a
      deterministic hash seeded by a per-cycle secret nonce. Banks (not
      free-typed values) eliminate founder discretion in what gets tested;
      the seeded hash means anyone with the published banks and algorithm can
      re-derive the exact prompts after the cycle closes.
    </p>

    <h2>Transparency &amp; verification</h2>
    <p>
      Because cycle names are predictable (e.g. <code>2026-06</code>, then
      <code>2026-07</code>), seeding placeholder selection on the cycle name
      would let a humanizer pre-compute next month's prompts and tune against
      them. We use a <strong>commit-reveal</strong> scheme instead:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>At cycle creation</strong>, we generate a random 32-byte
        <code>nonce</code> and publish only its SHA-256 to the public repo as
        <code>data/cycles/&lt;cycle&gt;/commit.json</code>. The nonce itself
        stays private.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>At cycle close</strong>, after all humanizers have been scored,
        we publish the nonce as <code>nonce.txt</code> alongside frozen
        snapshots of the templates (<code>templates.json</code>), the value
        banks (<code>banks.json</code>), the selection algorithm
        (<code>select-placeholders.js</code>), and the resolved prompts
        (<code>prompts.json</code>).
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The <code>scripts/verify-cycle.ts</code> script in the public repo
      re-runs the frozen algorithm against the published nonce, banks, and
      templates, then asserts that the resulting prompts match
      <code>prompts.json</code> exactly and that <code>sha256(nonce)</code>
      matches the committed hash from cycle start. It also runs the full
      score replay described below. Run it locally:
    </p>
    <pre
      class="mt-4 rounded-md border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4 font-mono text-sm overflow-x-auto text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"><code>git clone {GITHUB_REPO_URL}
cd humanizerbench
npm install
npm run verify              # verify every cycle
npm run verify -- 2026-06   # verify one cycle</code></pre>

    <h2>Tested humanizers</h2>
    <p>
      The active humanizer set is listed on the <a href="/leaderboard"
        >leaderboard</a
      >. Each humanizer has a dedicated detail page under
      <code>/humanizers/[slug]</code>. WriteHuman is included on the
      leaderboard and is held to exactly the same methodology, scoring, and
      penalty rules as every other humanizer.
    </p>

    <h2>Detectors</h2>
    <p>
      We test every humanized output against six independent commercial AI
      detectors: GPTZero, Originality.ai, Copyleaks, Winston AI, Sapling, and
      ZeroGPT. We do not operate, fine-tune, or coordinate with the detectors.
      For each humanizer output we submit the same text to all six and record
      a normalized score in <code>[0, 1]</code> where <code>1</code> means
      "human" (the humanizer evaded the detector) and <code>0</code> means
      "AI" (the detector caught it). The full per-test verdicts are published
      per cycle as <code>detector-scores.json</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>Scoring formula</h2>
    <p>
      The composite score for each humanizer is computed from four sub-scores,
      each in <code>[0, 1]</code>. The base composite is bounded
      <code>[0, 100]</code>; per-test penalties (defined below) are then
      subtracted and the result clamped to a final
      <code>composite</code> ∈ <code>[0, 100]</code>:
    </p>
    <pre
      class="mt-4 rounded-md border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4 font-mono text-sm overflow-x-auto text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"><code>composite_raw =
    42 * bypass_rate
  + 32 * meaning_preservation
  + 16 * readability
  + 10 * consistency_across_categories

composite = max(0, composite_raw - sum_of_penalty_deltas)</code></pre>
    <p>
      Weights and penalty rules are inlined verbatim into the published
      <code>scoring.js</code> file every cycle, so the methodology version on a
      given <code>leaderboard.json</code> pins the exact constants that ran.
      The current weights come from <code>methodology_version 1.2.0</code>;
      earlier versions are documented inline in the scoring code.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each sub-score has a precise algorithmic definition, given below.
      <em>Aggregate per humanizer</em> always means "over the humanizer's set
      of tests in this cycle with <code>status = "complete"</code>"; flagged
      and failed tests feed only the penalty rules. Tests reference the
      published row shapes in <code>tests.json</code> and
      <code>detector-scores.json</code>.
    </p>

    <h3 id="bypass-rate"><code>bypass_rate</code></h3>
    <p>
      For each test, compute the <strong>median</strong> of all
      <code>raw_score</code> values across the six detectors in
      <code>detector-scores.json</code> (median, not mean, because some
      detectors binarize their output near 0 or 1, and a single outlier would
      otherwise swing the mean by 0.25). The humanizer's
      <code>bypass_rate</code> is the <strong>mean</strong> of those per-test
      medians.
    </p>

    <h3 id="meaning-preservation"><code>meaning_preservation</code></h3>
    <p>
      For each test, the cosine similarity of the OpenAI
      <code>text-embedding-3-large</code> embeddings of
      <code>input_text</code> and <code>output_text</code>, clamped to
      <code>[0, 1]</code>. We publish the per-test value in
      <code>tests.json</code> as
      <code>tests[i].meaning_preservation</code>. The humanizer aggregate is
      the mean across that humanizer's complete tests.
    </p>

    <h3 id="readability"><code>readability</code></h3>
    <p>
      For each text we count grammar errors via LanguageTool (with
      proper-noun false positives filtered out; see <code
        >src/lib/scoring/lt-filter.ts</code
      > in the admin repo). The rate is <code
        >grammar_error_count / grammar_word_count</code
      >. The per-test readability is
      <code
        >max(0, min(1, 1 - max(0, output_rate - input_rate) * 50))</code
      >, i.e. <code>1</code> when the output is at least as clean as the
      input, falling to <code>0</code> when the output rate exceeds the input
      by <code>0.02</code> or more. Published in
      <code>tests[i].readability</code>; humanizer aggregate is the mean.
    </p>

    <h3 id="consistency"><code>consistency_across_categories</code></h3>
    <p>
      For each writing category present in the humanizer's tests, compute the
      mean of per-test bypass medians within that category. The humanizer's
      consistency score is
      <code>max(0, 1 - stddev(category_means))</code>, defaulting to
      <code>1</code> when fewer than two categories are present. A humanizer
      with identical category means scores <code>1</code>; a humanizer that
      crushes blog posts but flunks academic essays sees its consistency
      score dragged down.
    </p>

    <h2>Penalties</h2>
    <p>
      A humanizer's composite score is reduced by one or more penalties when
      its output exhibits known quality issues. Penalties deduct from
      <code>composite_raw</code>; the final composite is clamped to
      <code>[0, 100]</code>. Per-humanizer penalty deltas are published in
      <code>leaderboard.json</code> under
      <code>humanizers[i].penalties_applied</code>, so every deduction is
      auditable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each penalty has a fixed deduction per occurrence and a cap on its
      total impact, so no single category can dominate the final score. The
      maximum possible total penalty across all codes is <strong
        class="font-mono tabnum">−{MAX_TOTAL_PENALTY.toFixed(1)}</strong
      > (out of <code>100</code>).
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Penalty</th>
          <th>Trigger</th>
          <th class="text-right tabnum whitespace-nowrap">Per / Cap</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.severe_meaning_drift.label}</strong>
            (<code>severe_meaning_drift</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.severe_meaning_drift.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per test where
            <code>tests[i].meaning_preservation &lt; 0.85</code>.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.severe_meaning_drift.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.severe_meaning_drift.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.severe_grammar_degradation.label}</strong>
            (<code>severe_grammar_degradation</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.severe_grammar_degradation.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per test where <code>tests[i].readability &lt; 0.5</code>.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.severe_grammar_degradation.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.severe_grammar_degradation.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.length_inflation.label}</strong>
            (<code>length_inflation</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.length_inflation.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per test where
            <code
              >word_count(output_text) / word_count(input_text) &gt; 1.4</code
            >.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.length_inflation.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.length_inflation.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.identical_to_input.label}</strong>
            (<code>identical_to_input</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.identical_to_input.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per flagged test with
            <code>failure_reason_code = "identical_to_input"</code>.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.identical_to_input.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.identical_to_input.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.refusal_in_output.label}</strong>
            (<code>refusal_in_output</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.refusal_in_output.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per flagged test with
            <code>failure_reason_code ∈ &#123;"refusal_in_output", "refused_input"&#125;</code>.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.refusal_in_output.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.refusal_in_output.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.short_output.label}</strong>
            (<code>short_output</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.short_output.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Per flagged test with
            <code>failure_reason_code ∈ &#123;"short_output", "output_too_short"&#125;</code>.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.short_output.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.short_output.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <strong>{PENALTY_META.tool_unavailable_run.label}</strong>
            (<code>tool_unavailable_run</code>)
            <div class="text-xs mt-1 opacity-75">
              {PENALTY_META.tool_unavailable_run.description}
            </div>
          </td>
          <td>
            Once if
            <code
              >flagged_test_count / (complete_test_count + flagged_test_count)
              &gt; 0.25</code
            >.
          </td>
          <td class="text-right font-mono tabnum whitespace-nowrap">
            −{PENALTY_META.tool_unavailable_run.per.toFixed(1)} / −{PENALTY_META.tool_unavailable_run.cap.toFixed(1)}
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    {
      PENALTY_CODE_ORDER.length > 0 && null /* PENALTY_META reference kept to satisfy unused-warning checks */
    }

    <h2>Confidence levels</h2>
    <p>Each humanizer carries a confidence label:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>high</strong>: at least 60 complete tests in the cycle AND
        <code>stddev(category_means) &lt; 0.1</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>medium</strong>: at least 30 complete tests, but does not
        meet the high-confidence variance bar.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>low</strong>: fewer than 30 complete tests.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="reproducing">Reproducing the leaderboard from raw data</h2>
    <p>
      Anyone can re-derive every score on the leaderboard from the published
      cycle bundle. The shortest path:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <code>git clone {GITHUB_REPO_URL}</code> and <code>cd</code> in.
      </li>
      <li><code>npm install</code> (only dev deps are needed).</li>
      <li>
        <code>npm run verify -- &lt;cycle&gt;</code>. Under the hood this
        loads <code>scoring.js</code> from the cycle bundle, runs it against
        <code>samples.json</code>, <code>tests.json</code>, and
        <code>detector-scores.json</code>, and asserts that the per-humanizer
        results match <code>leaderboard.json</code> within <code>1e-4</code>.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      The published <code>scoring.js</code> is a self-contained ESM module
      with no external dependencies. To verify by hand without our script,
      import it and pass the three JSON arrays:
    </p>
    <pre
      class="mt-4 rounded-md border border-[var(--color-border)] bg-[var(--color-surface)] p-4 font-mono text-sm overflow-x-auto text-[var(--color-text-primary)]"><code>import {`{ computeLeaderboard }`} from "./data/cycles/2026-06/scoring.js";
import samples from "./data/cycles/2026-06/samples.json" with {`{ type: "json" }`};
import tests from "./data/cycles/2026-06/tests.json" with {`{ type: "json" }`};
import detectorScores from "./data/cycles/2026-06/detector-scores.json" with {`{ type: "json" }`};

const result = computeLeaderboard({`{ samples, tests, detectorScores }`});
console.log(result.humanizers[0]); // top-ranked humanizer for the cycle</code></pre>
    <p>
      Re-deriving a single sub-score by hand also works. To check one
      humanizer's <code>bypass_rate</code>:
    </p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        From <code>tests.json</code>, keep rows where
        <code>humanizer_slug = h</code> and <code>status = "complete"</code>.
        Call this list <code>T_h</code>.
      </li>
      <li>
        For each test in <code>T_h</code>, gather every
        <code>raw_score</code> in <code>detector-scores.json</code> with that
        <code>test_id</code>. Take the median.
      </li>
      <li>
        The humanizer's <code>bypass_rate</code> is the arithmetic mean of
        those medians.
      </li>
      <li>
        Compare to <code>leaderboard.json.humanizers[?].scores.bypass_rate</code>.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      Floating-point comparisons should use an absolute tolerance of
      <code>1e-4</code>; <code>verify-cycle.ts</code> uses the same.
    </p>

    <h2>Versioning</h2>
    <p>Every cycle's <code>leaderboard.json</code> records five version stamps:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Stamp</th>
          <th>Bumped when</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>methodology_version</code></td>
          <td>Anything on this page changes: formula weights, sub-score definitions, penalty rules, confidence thresholds.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>scoring_version</code></td>
          <td>The scoring script changes (typically alongside <code>methodology_version</code>).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>prompt_set_version</code></td>
          <td>A template is added/removed/edited, OR a value bank is changed, OR the placeholder-selection algorithm changes.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>detector_config_version</code></td>
          <td>A detector's endpoint, parser, or normalization changes, or a detector is added or removed.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>humanizer_config_version</code></td>
          <td>A humanizer's endpoint, parameters, or pricing tier we tested against changes, or a humanizer is added or removed.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      Past cycles are immutable. Each cycle bundle (templates, banks,
      algorithm, scoring code, raw data, leaderboard) is frozen at publish
      time, so a methodology change today never alters a cycle that ran
      yesterday; it just changes the version stamps on the next cycle.
    </p>

    <h2>Methodology integrity</h2>
    <p>
      WriteHuman does not manually adjust rankings. Rankings are computed
      mechanically from the published raw data using the published
      <code>scoring.js</code>. The integrity argument is structural rather
      than reputational: if a ranking didn't come from the published
      algorithm running on the published data, <code>npm run verify</code>
      would catch it, and anyone in the world can run that script.
    </p>

    <h2>How to contribute or dispute</h2>
    <p>
      If you've found an error, want to dispute a score, request a retest,
      or submit API access so we can test your humanizer programmatically,
      see <a href="/fairness"
        >our fairness &amp; corrections policy</a
      > for the contact addresses and the response-time commitment.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
